# ThreatForge Output — SIGNATURES
# CVE:       CVE-2026-55052
# Product:   microsoft sharepoint
# Tags:      [HIGH] [T1]
# Score:     40
# Tier:      STANDARD
# Generated: 2026-07-21T04:34:56.629726Z
# Status:    OK
# ---

# Confidence: No public PoC known — pattern inferred from the CVE/advisory
# description only.
# No packet-capture (PCAP) data source is available to this pipeline —
# this pattern is NOT verified against captured exploit traffic.
#
# Basis: CVE-2026-55052 describes a broken access control / missing
# authorization check in Microsoft SharePoint that allows an authenticated
# attacker to elevate privileges over a network [1][2]. SharePoint's REST
# and SOAP APIs are the most likely network-observable surface; this rule
# targets HTTP requests to SharePoint API endpoints that manipulate role
# or permission objects — a plausible but unconfirmed match pattern.
# The advisory page rendered no actionable technical detail [2], so
# specific request structures are not known. Analyst review and tuning
# against environment-specific SharePoint traffic is strongly recommended
# before any deployment. CVSS score is 8.8 HIGH [1]; no KEV listing
# confirmed; MITRE technique T1 (from priority tag) interpreted as
# privilege escalation via access-control bypass (T1068 / T1078).
# THIS IS A PROPOSED DRAFT FOR ANALYST REVIEW.

alert http $EXTERNAL_NET any -> $HOME_NET any (
  msg:"THREATFORGE CVE-2026-55052 Microsoft SharePoint broken access control privilege escalation attempt";
  flow:established,to_server;
  http.uri;
  content:"/_api/"; nocase;
  pcre:"/\/_api\/(web|site)\/(roles|roleassignments|currentuser|sitegroups|permissions)/Ui";
  http.method; content:"POST";
  reference:cve,2026-55052;
  metadata:mitre_technique_id T1068, is_kev false, status experimental;
  classtype:attempted-admin; sid:9000055; rev:1; )

